[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introducing the Women’s Engineering Society
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The Women’s Eng
[normal]ineering Society is a volunteer-le
[normal]d, small charity in existence for over 90 years. Our members represent all sectors, are qualified in subjects from maths, 
[normal]chemistry and biosciences through to PhD rocket scientists and all manner of engineering disciplines. They have entered technical professions through a variety of routes: engineering or science degrees, apprenticeships and even arts/humanities backgrounds.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Women’s Engineering Society was founded in 1919 and has a history of working closely with government on issues relating to women and work with particular relevance to science, technology and engineering. The Society draws its members from a broad ran
[normal]ge of sectors including defence, manufacturing, sciences, banking and finance and all stages of education
[normal],
[normal] and policy making. Members also reflect all career and life stages.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our submission 
[normal]includes
[normal] exemplar cases
[normal] drawn from personal perspectives and info
[normal]rmation gathered from enquiries to our offices, recent surveys of members and a call for responses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Factual information of which we would like the com
[normal]mittee to be aware 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The issue of women engineers and scientists goes 
[normal]back to
[normal] WW1 as seen in historical record of the Women’s Engineering Society (WES). Since the early years there have been almost annual enquiries into aspects of this issue for many years
[normal] and ‘wake-up calls’ followed by short term projects every decade since the 1970s
[normal] and even before
[normal]. The progress has been modest, at best, and short term at worst. There is too much fragmentation of effort and re-invention of wheels. There is a need for act
[normal]ion rather than examining, over and over again, why the situation exists. In the meantime, expensively-educated women are ‘lost’ to STEM careers in droves, for reasons not of their choosing. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Table 1 lists some of the many projects undertaken to help prog
[normal]ress women in their chosen careers as a timeline. 
[normal]Note that this list represents just the last 30 years and there were numerous schemes and projects from about 1970 onwards, and even many efforts both during and 
[normal]between
[normal] the two world wars.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“There have 
[normal]been many laudable schemes that have attempted to stem this loss of talent, but which, because of their often ad hoc, partial and short-term nature, have failed to have a sustained impact.”
[normal]  [Tapping all our Talents: Women in science, technology, engineeri
[normal]ng and mathematics: a strategy for Scotland
[normal]. RSE. 
[normal] 2012]
